SIMPLE: indolent
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Indolent
<hw>In"do*lent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Pref.
<ets>in-</ets> not + L. <ets>dolens</ets>, <ets>-entis</ets>, p. pr. of
<ets>dolere</ets> to feel pain: cf. F. <ets>indolent</ets>. See
<er>Dolorous</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Free from toil, pain, or trouble.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Indulging in ease; avoiding labor and exertion;
habitually idle; lazy; inactive; <as>as, an <ex>indolent</ex>
man</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To waste long nights in <qex>indolent</qex> repose.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Causing little or no pain or
annoyance; <as>as, an <ex>indolent</ex> tumor</as>.</def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Idle; lazy; slothful; sluggish; listless;
inactive; inert. See <er>Idle</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Indolently</ent>⟦br⟧
